caption.text:
Last post I showed you how 7 users crashed a 48GB GPU. 
This one’s about the fix.

The problem was never compute - it was wasted memory. 
Every request pre-allocates a massive continuous block for KV cache, 
even for a short prompt. 
Like booking an entire row at a restaurant for one person.

vLLM solved this with PagedAttention: 
splitting KV cache into small pages, 
allocated on demand, 
and shared across users with the same prefix.

Same GPU. Same model. 3–4x more users. No new hardware.

This is why vLLM became the default for LLM serving. 
Not because it’s magic -
because it makes memory actually usable. 
And in production, memory is almost always the real bottleneck.

.

caption.text:
22GB of free VRAM. 7 users. GPU dead. 
Most people think fitting weights in memory is the hard part - it’s not. 

The real bottleneck is what happens after. 
Hardly anyone talks about this, and as LLMs move into real production with real users, this is only going to get more important. 

Understand this before you scale.
.
.
.

Here’s the full breakdown 👇

—

𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗵𝗶𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗮𝗰𝘁𝘂𝗮𝗹𝗹𝘆 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗶𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗷𝗲𝗰𝘁𝘀:

→ A real, clickable link to a repo or live app (not required for senior roles)
→ A solid README with an architecture sketch: data → retrieval → serving
→ Real numbers: p95 latency, cost per request, eval metrics
→ Evidence of cloud infrastructure tools beyond localhost
→ CI/CD pipelines and MLOps awareness
→ A postmortem note: what broke and how you fixed it

—

𝗛𝗼𝘄 𝘁𝗼 𝗽𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗶𝘁 𝗼𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗖𝗩:

“Built Hybrid Search for X
→ p95 ≈ 700 ms
→ cost $0.004/request
→ eval hit@10 = 0.83
→ FastAPI + Postgres + OpenSearch + LangGraph
→ Ops: Docker, CI, alerts
→ Reduced latency by 42% with caching + batching”

This format instantly tells a hiring manager you think like an engineer; not just a student.

—

𝗔𝗜/𝗠𝗟 𝗦𝘆𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗺 𝗗𝗲𝘀𝗶𝗴𝗻

Hiring managers expect you to think out loud like this:
→ Start with the goal and SLOs (p95, quality, cost/user)
→ Draw data flow first: ingest → store → retrieve → infer → feedback
→ Call out trade-offs: latency vs quality, freshness vs cost
→ Add reliability: caching, fallbacks, observability

—

𝗣𝗿𝗼𝗺𝗽𝘁𝘀 𝘁𝗼 𝗿𝗲𝗵𝗲𝗮𝗿𝘀𝗲 (𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗳):

✅ Design a RAG for 1M PDFs; latency <1.5s — where do caching and rerankers live?
✅ Deploy an LLM assistant with small→big model routing, cost guardrails, and fail-open paths
✅ Make it resilient to data drift — describe eval gates, rollbacks, shadow tests

—

𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗵𝗶𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗹𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗻 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗶𝗻 𝗴𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝘀𝘄𝗲𝗿𝘀:

→ You clarify ambiguity first, then choose constraints
→ You know where latency hides: I/O, tokenization, rerank, tool calls
→ You measure cost and quality per request — and have a plan to bend both
→ Retries, alerts, graceful degradation

AI is evolving faster than humans were designed to handle change; and no one is saying it out loud.

The stats are real:
→ 45% higher burnout among frequent AI users (Quantum Workplace, 2024)
→ 83% of tech professionals experiencing burnout (DHR Global, 2025)
→ 77% of employees say AI actually increased their workload (Upwork Research Institute, 2024)
→ UC Berkeley researchers found AI doesn’t reduce work - it intensifies it (Harvard Business Review, Feb 2026)

This isn’t just me. This is all of us.
Comment below: how are you dealing with this? Lets help each other figure it out.

caption.text:
From personal experience 🙌
16 repos used by AI engineers

for faster inference, optimized LLM speed, GPU efficiency, and more 👇

→ FastAPI (⭐ 83k+)
↳ The default for serving ML models. If you’re not using it, you’re overcomplicating things.

→ vLLM (⭐ 66k+)
↳ Industry standard for high-throughput LLM serving. Continuous batching, maximum GPU utilization.

→ Ollama (⭐ 162k+)
↳ Easiest way to run LLMs locally. Clean dev experience. Fast experimentation.

→ Pydantic (⭐ 23k+)
↳ The backbone of reliable AI pipelines. Config, validation, structured outputs.
 
→ Flash Attention (⭐ 21k+)
↳ Fast, memory-efficient attention. Used by almost every other tool under the hood.

→ uv (⭐ 55k+)
↳ Replaces pip, pip-tools, virtualenv. Written in Rust. Once you switch, you never go back.

→ Unsloth (⭐ 51k+)
↳ Fine-tuning LLMs 2x faster with 70% less VRAM. That’s not a typo.

→ FAISS (⭐ 33k+)
↳ Meta’s similarity search. Handles millions of embeddings without breaking the bank.

→ PyTorch (⭐ 96k+)
↳ The core deep learning framework. Essential when you need custom optimization and low-level control.

→ Ruff (⭐ 40k+)
↳ 10-100x faster than flake8 + black. Written in Rust. CI feels instant.

→ exo (⭐ 39k+)
↳ Run your own AI cluster at home. Distributed inference across multiple devices.

→ Sentence Transformers (⭐ 16k+)
↳ Powers most RAG and semantic search in production.

→ LiteLLM (⭐ 20k+)
↳ One interface for 100+ LLM providers. Switch without changing code.

→ FastMCP (⭐ 15k+)
↳ The fast, Pythonic way to build MCP servers. Connect your LLMs to any tool or data source.

→ DuckDB (⭐ 28k+)
↳ Query parquet, CSV, dataframes. No database server needed. A secret weapon.

→ LangChain (⭐ 105k+)
↳ Love it or hate it. You need to understand what it abstracts away.

There are more to the above list.
Do add them in the comments :)
